WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.320
Hello and welcome to another Open-Source Chat.

00:00:05.320 --> 00:00:09.040
This time we're talking about Quarto with almost all of the Quarto Team.

00:00:09.040 --> 00:00:12.080
So first off, what are Open-Source Chats?

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:14.800
There are two big goals for Open-Source Chats.

00:00:14.800 --> 00:00:18.680
Firstly to connect users of a tool, Quarto in this case, directly with the people who

00:00:18.680 --> 00:00:21.480
develop and maintain that tool.

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:25.559
Developers can sometimes feel a little disconnected from end users.

00:00:25.559 --> 00:00:31.000
Maybe not so much in this case, Quarto has something like 12 commits a day on average

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.360
for the past two years and a pretty active issues and discussion section.

00:00:35.360 --> 00:00:40.200
But then, you know, users are often unaware of how these Open-Source tools get developed,

00:00:40.200 --> 00:00:43.200
get maintained, and so forth.

00:00:43.200 --> 00:00:46.720
Open-Source software just works better the more active and engaged the community is and

00:00:46.720 --> 00:00:51.400
the better the connection there is between developers and our end users.

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:57.520
Secondly, we'd like to use this opportunity for you to share with each other how you use

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:01.720
Quarto, how you approach and solve common problems.

00:01:01.720 --> 00:01:05.559
With that in mind, we invited questions from the community in this discussion.

00:01:05.559 --> 00:01:09.680
Since this is a recorded video, you obviously won't be able to pose any new questions.

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:14.440
But instead we invite you to check out the Quarto Dev Team's GitHub discussion section.

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:16.879
See the video description for details.

00:01:16.879 --> 00:01:18.760
And with us today we have Al Manning.

00:01:18.760 --> 00:01:24.599
Al is Quarto Team Manager, manager at the growing team at Quarto.

00:01:24.599 --> 00:01:29.000
Carlos Scheidegger, software engineer and recently previously out of academia.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.519
Charles Teague, software architect at Posit, and as I understand it, essentially co-lead

00:01:34.519 --> 00:01:37.680
of the Quarto project with JJ Lair.

00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:41.879
And then joining us a bit later is going to be Isabella Velasquez, who is essentially

00:01:41.879 --> 00:01:45.199
editor-in-chief at Posit blog as well as much else here.

00:01:45.199 --> 00:01:49.720
She'll be taking over duties about halfway through the presentation because, spoiler

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:52.959
alert, I'll be having a few technical difficulties.

00:01:52.959 --> 00:01:55.599
To get started off, what is Quarto?

00:01:55.599 --> 00:01:59.680
Quarto is an open source scientific and technical publishing system that builds on standard

00:01:59.680 --> 00:02:05.000
markdown with features essential for scientific communication.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:09.440
Computational engines include Python, R, Julia, and ObservableJS.

00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:12.440
Markdown that's Pandoc with many enhancements.

00:02:12.440 --> 00:02:16.559
But to documents, presentations, websites, books, blogs, and much else.

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:21.639
As a first question to get started, I asked the group, why open source?

00:02:21.639 --> 00:02:27.000
One thing that the three of you, I've noticed looking at your backgrounds and the CVs that

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:31.399
I could find online, there wasn't explicit mention of your contributions to open source

00:02:31.399 --> 00:02:37.880
software and yet Quarto and joining Posit, that's kind of a core to what we're doing.

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:42.360
And I actually know a few of you were making contributions to OS before, but that wasn't

00:02:42.479 --> 00:02:45.800
kind of a core thing to your occupation where it is now.

00:02:45.800 --> 00:02:49.160
So I kind of would like to pose that to you.

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:52.960
So maybe if I could start with Al, why open source?

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:55.160
Why have you decided to work in open source?

00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:56.160
Oh, wow.

00:02:56.160 --> 00:03:03.720
I have to try to keep my answer short because we don't have that much time.

00:03:03.720 --> 00:03:11.160
I've been primarily involved in sort of private company software engineering for a very long

00:03:11.160 --> 00:03:12.679
time.

00:03:12.679 --> 00:03:20.119
And this was, I've been involved before open source and I've experienced what it was like

00:03:20.119 --> 00:03:26.360
as a developer to be vendor locked and forced into doing large scale updates based on my

00:03:26.360 --> 00:03:28.960
relationship with a particular vendor.

00:03:28.960 --> 00:03:38.440
And then I also saw what happened as the open source movement and basically changed my craft.

00:03:38.679 --> 00:03:43.039
Completely transformed the way that I work, the communities that I was involved in.

00:03:43.039 --> 00:03:51.000
Really, really an important sort of aspect to how I've grown as a developer.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:56.320
And so when I had an opportunity to really join in and do open source development, I

00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:58.720
was very inspired.

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:06.479
Also by the mission of the company and how open source is such a close part of what the

00:04:06.479 --> 00:04:07.479
mission is.

00:04:08.479 --> 00:04:11.440
As Curtis mentioned, I'm a recovering academic.

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:17.559
I used to be a professor in computer science before I joined our studio in El Posit just

00:04:17.559 --> 00:04:19.640
about a year and a half ago.

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:26.399
And this problem of sort of technical communication, of sort of creating this mix of document and

00:04:26.399 --> 00:04:29.920
the computational content in a way that's reproducible, in a way that's easily shareable,

00:04:29.920 --> 00:04:33.720
that's sort of most impactful and visible for everyone.

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:37.920
So this problem has been near and dear to my heart for easily 15 years, sort of like

00:04:37.920 --> 00:04:41.239
the entirety of my professional career.

00:04:41.239 --> 00:04:46.239
And so when I had the chance to sort of work on a problem like this with the team that

00:04:46.239 --> 00:04:51.160
had built R Markdown, that had built sort of like the standard solution for R, and in

00:04:51.160 --> 00:04:55.440
a way that is both open source and is targeting sort of the broader data science ecosystem,

00:04:55.440 --> 00:04:57.559
for me it was a very easy solution.

00:04:57.559 --> 00:05:00.519
It was just like, yes, I will do this.

00:05:00.519 --> 00:05:03.399
Can I find a way to contribute in any way I can?

00:05:03.399 --> 00:05:08.440
And so that's sort of how I got interested in open source and in Quarto specifically.

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:09.720
And it's been fantastic.

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:13.959
So I've been working for just over a year and a half now.

00:05:13.959 --> 00:05:17.679
So I wasn't around when the project started, but I've been around for a while.

00:05:17.679 --> 00:05:21.079
And it's been just a ton of fun and incredibly rewarding.

00:05:21.079 --> 00:05:26.160
And I'm very excited about what Quarto is going to bring in the next few years, few

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:27.160
months.

00:05:27.160 --> 00:05:28.160
Yeah.

00:05:28.160 --> 00:05:29.160
I mean, I think I'll be brief.

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:32.440
Certainly a lot of the sentiment that Al and Carlos shared was true for me as well.

00:05:32.480 --> 00:05:40.839
I think the one other dimension for me individually was that I'm quite inspired by the pursuit

00:05:40.839 --> 00:05:43.160
of improving scientific communication.

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:46.839
And so that's part of what attracted me to Quarto was the ability to try to facilitate

00:05:46.839 --> 00:05:49.559
better technical and scientific communication.

00:05:49.559 --> 00:05:53.079
And to me, the foundation of that had to be open source.

00:05:53.079 --> 00:05:56.500
It was just simply something that was required in order to make that successful in those

00:05:56.500 --> 00:06:01.579
communities and to support that type of communication really broadly.

00:06:01.720 --> 00:06:07.380
And so to me, it was sort of while I had seen the growth of open source and really wanted

00:06:07.380 --> 00:06:12.859
to engage in it, I also saw it as essential to the success of this project.

00:06:12.859 --> 00:06:20.540
And so I'm excited to be contributing and doing that for the first time.

00:06:20.540 --> 00:06:24.260
The first question I saw that came into Slido actually a couple of days ago, it was actually

00:06:24.260 --> 00:06:31.019
a question that was posted to the RLIB issues asking about would Quarto actually end up

00:06:31.019 --> 00:06:35.540
on something like CRAN, where it's a bit easy to install for an R user?

00:06:35.540 --> 00:06:39.299
Is that something that you're thinking about or working on, or is it likely to continue

00:06:39.299 --> 00:06:45.260
to be the kind of separate way to separately install the CLI for Quarto?

00:06:45.260 --> 00:06:50.019
Yeah, I think, of course, Quarto is built into RStudio.

00:06:50.019 --> 00:06:52.820
So it's distributable there.

00:06:52.820 --> 00:06:57.859
There is an R package available for Quarto, specifically Quarto R. And so that's installable

00:06:57.859 --> 00:06:58.859
as well.

00:06:59.380 --> 00:07:05.899
Certainly, our goal is to make it really easy for R users, obviously, to use Quarto.

00:07:05.899 --> 00:07:11.100
So where we're not doing so, we would like to do so.

00:07:11.100 --> 00:07:18.339
Now that said, Quarto uses a TypeScript runtime, uses a whole bunch of technology under the

00:07:18.339 --> 00:07:19.339
hood.

00:07:19.339 --> 00:07:20.660
So it's not merely an R package.

00:07:20.660 --> 00:07:22.299
It's quite a bit more than that.

00:07:22.299 --> 00:07:27.700
And so it does need all of that to be functional.

00:07:27.700 --> 00:07:33.940
I saw that there was a question specifically about supporting use of Quarto in generating

00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:35.179
vignettes and other things.

00:07:35.179 --> 00:07:39.899
And I think that that's a slightly different matter, which is not something that's entirely

00:07:39.899 --> 00:07:42.299
within our control.

00:07:42.299 --> 00:07:48.820
From my understanding, I think the main issue there will be that if people want to use it

00:07:48.820 --> 00:07:54.140
as a vignette, you need to be able to actually have the full binaries run on CRAN.

00:07:54.179 --> 00:08:01.059
The main issue there is it runs on a lot of architectures for which we don't have a lot

00:08:01.059 --> 00:08:06.859
of control, like older architectures in particular, because Deno is a relatively new runtime.

00:08:06.859 --> 00:08:12.660
So Quarto is built on Deno, and Deno is a relatively new system that probably doesn't

00:08:12.660 --> 00:08:15.739
have a lot of support for older runtimes.

00:08:15.739 --> 00:08:21.660
We do a little bit of work on, for example, older versions of CentOS, but not on the broad

00:08:21.660 --> 00:08:24.380
support that you need from CRAN.

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:28.700
So we would love to do something like that, but I think that will require the kind of

00:08:28.700 --> 00:08:34.299
effort that we're currently doing for other things at the moment.

00:08:34.299 --> 00:08:39.820
So I wouldn't count on that being around in the next year, for example.

00:08:39.820 --> 00:08:40.820
Thank you.

00:08:40.820 --> 00:08:47.659
There's another question that was echoed in a question on Slido that was echoed in the

00:08:47.659 --> 00:08:51.260
Zoom chat as well from John David Smith.

00:08:51.260 --> 00:08:56.619
The question is, one nice output of Quarto would be to produce a Google Doc.

00:08:56.619 --> 00:09:00.700
The best current solution is not great, which is to create a .doc file and then drop it

00:09:00.700 --> 00:09:01.700
into Google Drive.

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:03.140
Do you have any kind of support for that?

00:09:03.140 --> 00:09:07.500
And it was echoed in Zoom because a lot of teams, right, they work out of Google Doc,

00:09:07.500 --> 00:09:09.179
ShareDoc, and which people work out of.

00:09:09.179 --> 00:09:10.580
Well, yeah, thanks for mentioning that.

00:09:10.580 --> 00:09:16.859
I mean, I think we've talked about different formats and in terms of, you know, our, you

00:09:16.859 --> 00:09:19.219
know, future backlog.

00:09:19.219 --> 00:09:24.580
And it's interesting to think about Google Doc and its relationship between like a publishing

00:09:24.580 --> 00:09:29.419
format, like something like you would see with Confluence or an actual doc format.

00:09:29.419 --> 00:09:33.659
I think we've talked about it a little bit, but not that much.

00:09:33.659 --> 00:09:39.619
And I too have used Google Docs and quite a lot before.

00:09:39.659 --> 00:09:44.059
So I do think it's something that's interesting for us to look into in terms of the actual

00:09:44.059 --> 00:09:46.659
like approach to publishing.

00:09:46.659 --> 00:09:51.539
I'm not really sure myself what the, what the format would be and how we would post

00:09:51.539 --> 00:09:56.179
it out, if it would be similar to what we're doing with Confluence or something else.

00:09:56.179 --> 00:09:58.500
But I think it's a very interesting idea.

00:09:58.500 --> 00:10:01.219
And thank you for mentioning it.

00:10:01.219 --> 00:10:05.099
Carlos and Charles, I don't know if you have any thoughts on Google Docs.

00:10:05.099 --> 00:10:07.020
We would love to support it.

00:10:07.020 --> 00:10:11.219
There's a certain amount of work making sure that everything works exactly how we would

00:10:11.219 --> 00:10:16.179
love a fully supported sort of system for Google Docs and collaboration to do that in

00:10:16.179 --> 00:10:17.299
like the right way.

00:10:17.299 --> 00:10:21.380
So again, that's the kind of thing that we want to make sure we do it right if we're

00:10:21.380 --> 00:10:22.380
going to do it.

00:10:22.380 --> 00:10:28.979
So I don't think we have short plans to announce anything like this, but it's certainly something

00:10:28.979 --> 00:10:30.979
we would love to be able to do.

00:10:30.979 --> 00:10:35.619
So we hear your pain and we want to address it.

00:10:35.619 --> 00:10:41.500
We will let you know when we have something on that.

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:45.140
And so just sort of to follow up on some of the solutions that people suggested.

00:10:45.140 --> 00:10:49.700
So some folks use track down as a way to sort of export in and out in a way that will let

00:10:49.700 --> 00:10:50.700
you do that.

00:10:50.700 --> 00:10:54.659
And it's not ideal, but at least you can sort of see the changes and you can actually like

00:10:54.659 --> 00:10:55.820
pull it back and forth.

00:10:55.820 --> 00:10:59.340
So there are some workarounds, but we know they're not ideal.

00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:01.460
So we'd love to be able to do something better.

00:11:01.460 --> 00:11:06.900
We just don't have any plans given the other things that we need to do at this point.

00:11:06.900 --> 00:11:13.059
There's another question that I actually heard echoed as well ahead of time.

00:11:13.059 --> 00:11:19.099
The question from from Matthew Markington asking about Lua filters and short codes.

00:11:19.099 --> 00:11:21.140
Lua filters and short codes are amazing.

00:11:21.140 --> 00:11:26.260
I'm interested to hear from the Cordo team, their approach working environment for developing

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:30.260
in Lua in a way that enables quickly prototyping and debugging.

00:11:30.260 --> 00:11:33.580
This iteration is a point of friction for Matthew.

00:11:33.580 --> 00:11:39.219
So I 100% agree with you, given that I had to essentially learn Lua when I joined the

00:11:39.219 --> 00:11:43.299
Cordo project, and I already joined when there were hundreds of Lua files.

00:11:43.299 --> 00:11:48.780
And I agree with you that the Lua experience could be improved a lot.

00:11:48.780 --> 00:11:52.299
And we are actually putting a ton of effort on this coming up.

00:11:52.299 --> 00:11:58.900
So one of the things that we have support for, and unfortunately, it's only if you're

00:11:58.900 --> 00:12:05.820
using VS code right now, but you can actually use, if you're willing to use Visual Studio

00:12:05.820 --> 00:12:13.099
code, which it's not our studio, for example, for like developing Lua, you actually have,

00:12:13.099 --> 00:12:19.260
if you open sort of Lua files and filters, we have the ability of doing the kinds of

00:12:19.260 --> 00:12:23.539
auto completions that you get from, say, like TypeScript, right?

00:12:23.539 --> 00:12:27.460
So like type inference on template values, type inference on your functions, and sort

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:30.900
of like reminding you that if you open a file, you need to check if the file was opened

00:12:30.900 --> 00:12:33.059
successfully and that kind of thing.

00:12:33.059 --> 00:12:35.020
And that helps a lot.

00:12:35.020 --> 00:12:38.619
So we should probably do a better job of documenting how to get to that.

00:12:38.619 --> 00:12:41.159
And that's something we're working on at 1.3.

00:12:41.159 --> 00:12:45.260
But this kind of developer experience for Lua, specifically for sort of filters, short

00:12:45.260 --> 00:12:46.760
codes, extensions.

00:12:46.760 --> 00:12:51.580
So Charles has put a lot of effort in 1.2 and providing a really good solid support

00:12:51.580 --> 00:12:53.400
for extensions.

00:12:53.400 --> 00:12:59.039
And now in 1.3, we're sort of making it nicely sort of usable in terms of getting all of

00:12:59.039 --> 00:13:03.880
the intelligence that you can get out of Visual Studio code specifically.

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:06.119
So that's how I develop.

00:13:06.119 --> 00:13:12.039
So if folks have questions on that, we can either like sort of open a discussion on GitHub,

00:13:12.039 --> 00:13:17.880
which Curtis and Isabella can point out to where things are, or we can have like reach

00:13:17.880 --> 00:13:22.119
out to me in other ways and sort of try to figure out a way to document this for people

00:13:22.159 --> 00:13:23.679
who are invested.

00:13:23.679 --> 00:13:25.159
We know it's an ask right now.

00:13:25.159 --> 00:13:28.080
It's sort of you have to learn a few other things and it's not trivial.

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:32.280
But we actually actively wanted to make it easier because it will be the way that you

00:13:32.280 --> 00:13:34.919
develop extensions for the foreseeable future.

00:13:36.400 --> 00:13:43.799
I think the one other note to add there would be, I think, starting in 1.2 of Cordo, the

00:13:43.799 --> 00:13:48.400
preview server should now be hot reloading if you're changing filters inside extensions,

00:13:48.400 --> 00:13:49.440
for example.

00:13:49.479 --> 00:13:55.400
And so you should be getting sort of the ability to sort of modify filters and then see reloading

00:13:55.400 --> 00:13:58.840
right there without having to go through a whole render cycle again.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:04.000
And I believe that was starting in 1.2, but that was something that JJ added that made

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.760
a huge difference in terms of extension development.

00:14:07.280 --> 00:14:12.799
And I think the one other note that I think is worth throwing out there is we've done a

00:14:12.799 --> 00:14:17.479
lot of the development of the Lua stuff as extensions, and that's a useful way to test

00:14:17.479 --> 00:14:22.599
as well. Because so, you know, obviously, you know, that's one of the things to consider.

00:14:23.359 --> 00:14:30.400
Another set of questions kind of feeds into a theme that I saw Richard on Slido that asked

00:14:30.400 --> 00:14:35.960
a few days ago, is there a single documentation page for all the Cordo specific YAML

00:14:35.960 --> 00:14:41.880
options? And I think the theme of that fits into kind of documentation, like the Cordo

00:14:41.880 --> 00:14:43.559
Docs site is quite big.

00:14:43.799 --> 00:14:49.400
Is there any kind of advice that you guys have for people kind of engaging with that and

00:14:49.400 --> 00:14:51.799
trying to kind of like dive into those features?

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:55.960
It's both like a very strong point of Cordo.

00:14:55.960 --> 00:15:01.640
It's incredibly well documented, but folks are kind of curious if there's something more

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:03.960
like a cheat sheet, for example, or something like that.

00:15:03.960 --> 00:15:05.840
Right. So we don't have a cheat sheet.

00:15:05.840 --> 00:15:10.359
And I would love to do something like that, given the ones that, you know, our studio used

00:15:10.359 --> 00:15:11.880
to put out for like our markdown.

00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:14.400
And I'm sure Positive will do that for new libraries.

00:15:14.679 --> 00:15:17.719
We don't have one for Cordo yet, but that would be a fantastic one to work on.

00:15:17.719 --> 00:15:18.640
That's a great idea.

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:24.640
The problem was so the question was about a single web page with all the YAML references.

00:15:24.640 --> 00:15:26.440
We would love to do something like that.

00:15:26.440 --> 00:15:29.880
We originally had considered doing precisely that as a single page.

00:15:29.880 --> 00:15:32.400
The issue is Cordo has a pretty big surface.

00:15:32.679 --> 00:15:38.359
So on last count, that was like on the order of a few thousand YAML options that you could

00:15:38.359 --> 00:15:42.440
use to configure. And that's not an exaggeration, it's over a thousand.

00:15:43.200 --> 00:15:48.719
So we can't like it's not the issue would be that people would miss the forest for the trees.

00:15:48.719 --> 00:15:51.400
Right. Like it would be hard to sort of see what's going on on those.

00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:58.280
We do have this I posted on chat as Cordo.org slash docs slash reference.

00:15:58.640 --> 00:16:01.760
Or if you just go on the main Cordo web page, it's right on the main menu.

00:16:01.760 --> 00:16:04.919
It's reference. So that is actually the options reference.

00:16:04.919 --> 00:16:06.559
All of those are YAML.

00:16:06.559 --> 00:16:10.599
And so you can sort of get an entry point if you want to do something for document formats or for

00:16:10.599 --> 00:16:14.000
presentations, for markdowns, for execution and start from there.

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.880
And that you have the list of all of those.

00:16:17.400 --> 00:16:21.919
So if that's a good entry point, it is not a single web page, but it's relatively

00:16:21.919 --> 00:16:26.280
comprehensive and it's generated automatically from our YAML infrastructure.

00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:28.440
So that gets sort of automatically updated.

00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:30.280
So it's certainly like up to date.

00:16:30.799 --> 00:16:38.159
One thing that we've heard around our documentation as well is it may be it may be a bit

00:16:38.359 --> 00:16:44.039
overwhelming in terms of how much there is and how it covers everything very comprehensively

00:16:44.400 --> 00:16:45.440
and very deeply.

00:16:46.640 --> 00:16:54.080
And it may be interesting and taking a look at creating on top of the existing sort of

00:16:54.080 --> 00:17:00.559
full doc set documentation sets that are focused on more specific cases and uses of Cordo.

00:17:01.159 --> 00:17:06.119
So if this is something that resonates with you, we would love to hear from you about that.

00:17:07.119 --> 00:17:11.959
As it's as Carlos said, the surface is massive.

00:17:12.359 --> 00:17:15.839
And so it can be difficult to know exactly how to come in.

00:17:16.359 --> 00:17:24.119
And we also want to take into account your contacts and your background for entering in and

00:17:24.119 --> 00:17:24.800
using Cordo.

00:17:26.760 --> 00:17:32.359
And if I could take a pause for a moment, there's a lot of good questions coming in and I'd

00:17:32.359 --> 00:17:36.239
like to get to them, but I seem to be having a technical issue.

00:17:36.239 --> 00:17:42.479
So can I ask Isabella to take over the host position to kind of help things go a bit more

00:17:42.479 --> 00:17:44.479
smoothly? Would you be able to do that, Isabella?

00:17:44.719 --> 00:17:45.959
Yeah. Hi, everyone.

00:17:46.760 --> 00:17:49.719
I am happy to share some questions.

00:17:49.760 --> 00:17:52.040
There's really great ones coming in.

00:17:52.560 --> 00:17:56.079
And so I will just go down the line.

00:17:56.119 --> 00:18:05.839
So from chat, we got loving Cordo and thank you Cordo devs and absolutely love the tool.

00:18:06.239 --> 00:18:12.560
So OJS is a total win and you work with DuckDB, it is great.

00:18:12.839 --> 00:18:16.280
Is there something like observable SQL cells on the roadmap?

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:21.880
So thank you for asking that, that's a very good question.

00:18:22.920 --> 00:18:29.560
To the best of my understanding, the SQL, so if you folks don't know what observable is, just to

00:18:29.560 --> 00:18:37.160
backtrack a little bit, this is a new JavaScript like runtime for web pages that offers

00:18:37.160 --> 00:18:42.800
reactivity, sort of like what you would get with React, but sort of as a lower level, higher

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:45.520
performance. So it can do really nice interactive visualizations.

00:18:46.040 --> 00:18:49.359
And it has a shiny feel to it if you're not a shiny programmer.

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:52.959
So everything is actually reactive and so you don't need to set up event handlers and things of

00:18:52.959 --> 00:18:55.239
that sort. So it's exceedingly nice.

00:18:55.839 --> 00:19:00.839
And Cordo has support for the runtime for sort of like the execution model for that.

00:19:01.640 --> 00:19:06.119
Observable is built by Observable HQ, which is a startup and they make the runtime open source.

00:19:06.280 --> 00:19:08.719
And so they've been generous enough to do that.

00:19:08.719 --> 00:19:10.319
And we are super appreciative of that.

00:19:10.319 --> 00:19:12.199
And sort of we use that in Cordo.

00:19:13.199 --> 00:19:17.959
The SQL cell specifically, to the best of my understanding, is not open source.

00:19:18.079 --> 00:19:24.839
That's part of their value add proprietary cell for sort of navigating a database in JavaScript in

00:19:24.839 --> 00:19:28.040
runtime. And so they don't offer that as part of their open source offering.

00:19:28.040 --> 00:19:29.800
So we can't use that.

00:19:30.800 --> 00:19:38.239
With that said, we would love to sort of we have the kind of like code reuse that you can get out

00:19:38.239 --> 00:19:41.359
of Observable in general, sort of reusing notebooks.

00:19:41.359 --> 00:19:47.160
So if you have a web page in which you sort of have an SQL navigator that you wrote, you can

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:48.439
actually reuse it across.

00:19:48.439 --> 00:19:55.319
We just don't have access to the really exceedingly nice SQL cell explorer that Observable

00:19:55.839 --> 00:20:00.640
HQ does. And I don't think we'll be able to because it's not part of the open source offering.

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:09.239
Another chat question from David Reinstein, what is the best way to retain data and environment

00:20:09.239 --> 00:20:11.839
objects across chapters in a Cordo book?

00:20:11.880 --> 00:20:14.800
Is there any path to enabling this?

00:20:15.359 --> 00:20:19.680
It's the main thing from our markdown that David is looking for in Cordo.

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:25.359
Yeah, I think I think the issue, if I understand it correctly, boils down to the fact that I think

00:20:25.359 --> 00:20:31.040
bookdown sort of conceptually renders the book as a single large executable document, whereas

00:20:31.040 --> 00:20:32.680
Cordo renders them individually.

00:20:32.680 --> 00:20:36.040
And so there's not shared context between the individual pages.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:41.719
So, you know, I don't I actually don't know what the best solution to that problem is.

00:20:41.719 --> 00:20:47.119
I think, you know, the one that jumps out to me straight away is includes and I don't know if

00:20:47.640 --> 00:20:52.560
Carlos wants to weigh on in this, but simply, you know, creating that shared context and set up

00:20:52.560 --> 00:20:55.880
cell in a in a file that's included in every chapter.

00:20:55.880 --> 00:20:58.760
And I know it's not ideal to have to include something in every chapter.

00:20:59.040 --> 00:21:00.439
That's the best thing that I can think of.

00:21:00.439 --> 00:21:02.000
I don't know if you have alternatives, Carlos.

00:21:02.560 --> 00:21:08.000
So, yeah, so one of the Charles said this is another issue where the difference between our

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:12.760
markdown and Cordo sort of makes it particularly painful for folks that are used to the way

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:16.520
that sort of our markdown and bookdown works, which was taking a single document.

00:21:17.239 --> 00:21:20.560
And running it all in a single context, which Cordo does not do.

00:21:21.280 --> 00:21:27.680
So Charles mentioned includes, which essentially are you can sort of just pick a cell and like

00:21:27.680 --> 00:21:29.959
put it on an include document and then just run it.

00:21:30.520 --> 00:21:34.760
And someone mentioned on on voice right now that that slows down because you have to

00:21:34.760 --> 00:21:36.000
re-execute that every time.

00:21:36.079 --> 00:21:37.760
So that's absolutely an issue.

00:21:38.719 --> 00:21:44.359
One of the things that you can do is sort of unfortunately, it's sort of manual, but you

00:21:44.359 --> 00:21:50.560
can introduce some state and check whether your file exists and sort of not run it and

00:21:50.560 --> 00:21:56.199
sort of just return it from like, for example, an SQLite database or a data frame and sort

00:21:56.199 --> 00:21:59.880
of do the management yourself, which is an additional pain point.

00:21:59.880 --> 00:22:01.800
It's not ideal, but that's something you can do.

00:22:02.760 --> 00:22:10.880
The other thing you can do and that's starting on version 1.3 is so this is something that

00:22:10.880 --> 00:22:12.359
just is hot off the presses.

00:22:12.359 --> 00:22:21.000
And Charles worked on this is we we can actually sort of run things and pull results from an

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:23.920
existing notebook, from an existing IPyNB file.

00:22:24.319 --> 00:22:29.839
And so if you have a setup code that takes a lot of time, you can sort of set up a

00:22:29.839 --> 00:22:35.839
different quarter page and render to a PyNB so that the result it generates is a

00:22:35.839 --> 00:22:41.520
notebook. And then we actually have a new short code that is on the documentation that

00:22:41.520 --> 00:22:46.680
you can just call the embed short code, which can pull parts of an existing IPyNB file

00:22:46.680 --> 00:22:47.920
without re-executing it.

00:22:47.920 --> 00:22:49.599
So it actually pulls it from the result.

00:22:50.640 --> 00:22:55.199
And so this works for any IPyNB, whether it was generated by Quarto or whether it was

00:22:55.199 --> 00:23:00.599
generated by yourself or, you know, sort of from like an existing Jupyter notebook.

00:23:01.280 --> 00:23:02.359
And it just works like that.

00:23:02.359 --> 00:23:06.959
And so if you have a PyNB file that generates the result that you want to pull to a

00:23:06.959 --> 00:23:09.319
different page, that's a very nice way of doing it.

00:23:09.319 --> 00:23:13.800
Now, it is not as straightforward to pull, for example, data or things of that sort.

00:23:14.160 --> 00:23:19.040
And so it's not perfect, but that's the kind of solution that we're starting to work on

00:23:19.040 --> 00:23:23.359
is sort of how to reuse existing bits from other web pages and in this case from

00:23:23.359 --> 00:23:26.760
notebooks that we would love to sort of figure out the story.

00:23:26.760 --> 00:23:31.640
And currently we have the support for embed, but this more general sort of how to manage

00:23:31.640 --> 00:23:35.359
dependencies in order of execution is definitely something that we would love to

00:23:35.359 --> 00:23:37.239
improve in Quarto and future versions.

00:23:37.239 --> 00:23:39.239
We'll probably do some work on that next year.

00:23:40.479 --> 00:23:43.520
We are aware of the pain that this is causing our users.

00:23:43.520 --> 00:23:47.959
We want to work on it, but we want to make sure that this works across specifically

00:23:47.959 --> 00:23:51.520
across not only our markdown, but users that come from a Jupyter background and users

00:23:51.520 --> 00:23:54.160
that might have like Julia execution cells and things of that sort.

00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:57.079
So it's a little larger scope of a problem.

00:23:58.520 --> 00:24:00.160
Excellent, thank you so much.

00:24:00.680 --> 00:24:07.400
So there is a lot of excitement about Flex Dashboard for Quarto.

00:24:07.400 --> 00:24:12.680
I'd love to hear about, yeah, I'll just read the question from Jake directly.

00:24:12.880 --> 00:24:15.640
What are the plans for Flex Dashboard or replacement?

00:24:15.920 --> 00:24:20.359
It's our most common deliverable and not having it has stopped us from sharing with our team.

00:24:22.160 --> 00:24:24.000
Well, yeah, I can I can speak to this.

00:24:24.280 --> 00:24:27.920
We we don't have an official Quarto as a team.

00:24:27.920 --> 00:24:34.959
So and the main reason why is we're we're trying to be very have a lot of agility and

00:24:34.959 --> 00:24:36.800
adapt as information comes in.

00:24:37.760 --> 00:24:45.319
And we saw that with 1.2 and 1.1 that as we were learning, we really needed to focus in

00:24:45.319 --> 00:24:49.680
on stabilization for the very beginning.

00:24:50.119 --> 00:24:55.920
The team has been talking about Flex Dashboard and it's on our mind and we've had

00:24:55.920 --> 00:24:57.520
recent conversations about it.

00:24:57.920 --> 00:25:04.719
So it's top of mind in terms of our our forecast.

00:25:06.199 --> 00:25:11.160
And I don't know if Charles or Carlos want to speak to any of the planning so far or

00:25:11.160 --> 00:25:16.599
anything. Well, I think the one thing I can say is it has been Flex Dashboard has been on

00:25:16.599 --> 00:25:18.760
the roadmaps since pre 1.0.

00:25:19.199 --> 00:25:22.599
So I think we originally set out and said, OK, when 1.0 comes out, this is going to be

00:25:22.599 --> 00:25:24.800
great. It'll have like it'll have support for dashboards.

00:25:25.199 --> 00:25:28.560
And then we're like, OK, we didn't quite get that done for our studio comp.

00:25:28.920 --> 00:25:33.760
But for 1.1, we'll definitely dashboards for 1.2 dashboards.

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:36.760
You know, so I think it's it's it's right there.

00:25:36.760 --> 00:25:43.880
We know it's something that is necessary and we just have not quite managed to get

00:25:43.880 --> 00:25:45.880
there in terms of the work that we have in front of us.

00:25:45.880 --> 00:25:50.400
So, you know, I don't think we can commit to exactly when that will be there, except to

00:25:50.400 --> 00:25:57.000
say that we know it's something that is essential and it is sitting at the front of

00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:58.959
every time we talk about what should we be doing.

00:25:58.959 --> 00:26:00.760
It's sitting right there with us.

00:26:01.359 --> 00:26:04.760
It's there in like one or two other things that we're like, God, we really have to get

00:26:04.760 --> 00:26:08.560
to these things. So I do I do expect us to get there soon.

00:26:09.959 --> 00:26:15.599
Thank you. And it's not quite a question, but I would love to just hear your thoughts on

00:26:15.599 --> 00:26:22.359
this statement. So someone on Slido posted that the biggest impediment for team adoption

00:26:23.319 --> 00:26:27.680
with Porto is competing with iPython notebooks for Mindspace.

00:26:28.040 --> 00:26:32.319
And just welcome your thoughts on like, yeah, on that topic.

00:26:35.040 --> 00:26:39.560
Well, I mean, I think ultimately we'd love to see as a complementary to notebooks in some

00:26:39.560 --> 00:26:45.800
capacity, you know, and so I don't I think notebooks have an important role in data

00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:47.439
science and in science.

00:26:47.800 --> 00:26:52.760
And so we don't what it doesn't need to supplant that it can merely be in addition to it.

00:26:53.079 --> 00:26:54.680
But there are advantages to Cordo.

00:26:54.680 --> 00:26:58.160
There are capabilities that Cordo has that notebooks don't have.

00:26:58.160 --> 00:27:04.640
And so for particular kinds of communication, I would highlight things like citations of

00:27:04.640 --> 00:27:06.839
bibliographies, cross references.

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:12.319
You know, that type of feature is a feature that is something that Cordo adds to a notebook.

00:27:12.640 --> 00:27:17.920
And so you could either, you know, in the notebook based world, you could say I'm going to

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:22.160
write Cordo markdown in that notebook and use Cordo as an engine to render that notebook.

00:27:22.400 --> 00:27:25.839
And you'll get resolved citations and references and cross references.

00:27:25.839 --> 00:27:28.719
And you'll get all the the Cordo goodness on top of that notebook.

00:27:28.719 --> 00:27:30.119
That's that's one possibility.

00:27:31.079 --> 00:27:35.520
You know, as Carlos alluded to, we're working on embedding resources from notebooks.

00:27:35.520 --> 00:27:41.160
And so that would let you take and use the Cordo document as a narrative focused document.

00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:47.359
And so focus on narrative and layout and appearance and embed the outputs of computations

00:27:47.359 --> 00:27:51.319
that come from notebooks right within right within your Cordo document.

00:27:51.959 --> 00:27:55.040
And so that lets you sort of use the two as complementary to one another.

00:27:56.000 --> 00:28:00.359
And so I think, you know, you know, we have we have work to do to continue to improve our

00:28:00.359 --> 00:28:05.439
notebook support. But to me, you know, I think what we ideally would see is that notebooks

00:28:05.439 --> 00:28:06.719
are yet another tool.

00:28:06.719 --> 00:28:08.040
Cordo is another tool.

00:28:08.400 --> 00:28:13.239
And those tools are really quite complementary to one another, as opposed to being

00:28:13.239 --> 00:28:16.680
substitutes for one another. I mean, I don't know if Carlos, you have other stuff to add to

00:28:16.680 --> 00:28:18.640
that, but that's maybe at a high level.

00:28:19.280 --> 00:28:21.359
No, I think that's I think that's exactly right.

00:28:21.359 --> 00:28:27.959
And I speaking from sort of, you know, I used to be a professor.

00:28:27.959 --> 00:28:31.599
I mentioned this earlier. And a lot of my students, when we were doing research, they were all using

00:28:31.599 --> 00:28:34.479
notebooks and PyTorch to sort of do their machine learning experiments.

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:39.280
So I share the understanding of how convenient folks find notebooks to be.

00:28:40.160 --> 00:28:47.439
And one of the things that, right, like Charles mentioned, is sort of this issue of sort of

00:28:47.439 --> 00:28:51.640
complementarity. And so, right, the embed shortcode that Charles just implemented is sort of

00:28:51.640 --> 00:28:58.199
going towards that. And one of the things that we can do that maybe we should advertise more

00:28:58.199 --> 00:29:03.520
broadly is we can use IPyNBs as both input and as output in Quarto.

00:29:03.520 --> 00:29:07.040
Right. So I'm not sure, just sort of making sure that folks are aware that this is a

00:29:07.040 --> 00:29:11.599
possibility. But if you like type Quarto render and you give an IPyNB, we will convert that

00:29:11.599 --> 00:29:15.560
notebook to like Markdown, we will do all the processing and we'll produce all the outputs that

00:29:15.560 --> 00:29:20.000
you need. If you need to produce an IPyNB file, we also can do that.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:24.280
So you can take a QMD and you can render an IPyNB file that you can share with people that are

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:26.199
entirely on the IPyNB ecosystem.

00:29:27.040 --> 00:29:34.599
And so I understand sort of the trying to convince folks of whether this is a language

00:29:34.599 --> 00:29:37.040
agnostic tool or something that's really from the R universe.

00:29:37.040 --> 00:29:42.280
We are working very hard to make sure that this works well with folks existing workflow in a

00:29:42.280 --> 00:29:43.920
company and their personal workflows.

00:29:44.760 --> 00:29:49.400
If there are specific things that that are pain points, I would love to hear about them, like

00:29:49.439 --> 00:29:52.000
either like, you know, should we post a question on GitHub?

00:29:52.280 --> 00:29:57.199
We absolutely want to make the IPyThon ecosystem work well in Quarto.

00:29:58.439 --> 00:30:01.119
Great. And that kind of leads into the next question.

00:30:01.119 --> 00:30:09.160
So a specific one from Slido, Jake asks, I'm not sure where to post issues on GitHub is an

00:30:09.160 --> 00:30:14.199
issue with the rendering button in RStudio, something for the RStudio team or the Quarto

00:30:14.199 --> 00:30:18.959
team? And then I guess more broader, like what is the best way of getting in touch?

00:30:19.599 --> 00:30:23.800
Like what sorts of advice would you give for folks who want to reach out?

00:30:24.160 --> 00:30:32.880
I can answer that. So we are happy if folks are not sure where to post a GitHub issue

00:30:33.160 --> 00:30:38.280
posted on our repository, if we don't think it's the right place for it, we will sort of let

00:30:38.280 --> 00:30:41.079
you know, we will help you figure out where is the right place for that.

00:30:41.400 --> 00:30:45.560
But we would much rather hear from you folks that are having issues that we want to help

00:30:45.920 --> 00:30:50.800
then not hear about it because you folks have some hesitancy about where or whether you're

00:30:50.800 --> 00:30:55.520
doing the right thing. We would love to get everyone in the discussions.

00:30:55.520 --> 00:31:01.479
And so if you the main place where we have discussions, I think it's available posted on

00:31:01.479 --> 00:31:06.880
chat earlier is the discussions forum on the Quarto CLI repository on GitHub.

00:31:07.839 --> 00:31:12.520
And the issues for that same repository is where we do tracking of all of the problems.

00:31:12.520 --> 00:31:18.719
So if you want to take that as an entry point for these questions, we would be happy to

00:31:18.719 --> 00:31:22.880
take either and sort of figure out whether it's an RStudio issue or not.

00:31:23.319 --> 00:31:29.479
So please don't don't hold back on reporting bugs from us, which we do want to hear

00:31:29.479 --> 00:31:31.160
because you're not sure where to post them.

00:31:32.079 --> 00:31:34.439
We would be happy to figure things out.

00:31:36.359 --> 00:31:42.280
Awesome. And in terms of the community, like what sorts of things would you hope to see in

00:31:42.560 --> 00:31:50.160
future projects, co-contributions, like what is the most helpful and inspiring for you?

00:31:53.040 --> 00:31:58.479
Well, so Carlos pointed to issues, that's issues are obviously helpful because it's how

00:31:58.479 --> 00:32:02.199
Quarto is actually being applied and the scope of what you can do with Quarto is so big, we

00:32:02.199 --> 00:32:04.479
need people doing all kinds of crazy things.

00:32:04.880 --> 00:32:09.560
I personally am really interested to see what people come up with for extensions.

00:32:09.880 --> 00:32:15.079
There's quite a bit of latent capability in the extension ecosystem, and it's one of the

00:32:15.079 --> 00:32:20.079
things that I do think differentiates Quarto from something like just pure Pandoc is the

00:32:20.079 --> 00:32:23.439
ability to really bundle and extend the capabilities.

00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:30.239
A lot of what is built in Quarto that we built sort of pre in the pre 1.0 world could

00:32:30.239 --> 00:32:32.040
potentially be built as extensions now.

00:32:33.280 --> 00:32:36.599
And we just didn't have that infrastructure at the time we were doing Quarto 1.0.

00:32:36.599 --> 00:32:40.920
So to me, there's a huge amount that people can do with extensions and we would love to see

00:32:40.920 --> 00:32:43.040
those extensions and promote those extensions.

00:32:43.760 --> 00:32:48.839
And then even I think just today, just this morning, I merged a pull request from somebody

00:32:48.839 --> 00:32:51.640
and pull requests are, of course, always, always welcome.

00:32:51.880 --> 00:32:57.239
I understand and I want to acknowledge it's working on Quarto is not necessarily easy.

00:32:57.280 --> 00:33:00.000
There's a lot of different languages and a lot of different runtimes.

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:03.719
And so just from a complexity perspective, there's a lot to take in.

00:33:04.119 --> 00:33:08.839
But even small, simple PRs help and we've gotten a ton of those.

00:33:08.839 --> 00:33:15.920
And I certainly eminently really appreciate that when people take the time to make those

00:33:15.920 --> 00:33:21.000
PRs to whether it's a translation or whether it's a code change, it's really, really

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:26.239
welcome. I'd just like to add to that that there's a lot of very active members of the

00:33:26.239 --> 00:33:31.079
community now who are supporting us in issues, in discussions.

00:33:31.439 --> 00:33:33.040
And thank you very much.

00:33:34.119 --> 00:33:37.719
It is, it is, it's inspiring.

00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:41.520
And I think we're very grateful to have such an engaged community.

00:33:42.000 --> 00:33:43.640
And we definitely feel the boost.

00:33:44.839 --> 00:33:47.839
So thank you.

00:33:47.839 --> 00:33:53.719
Thank you. But there are a few questions in the chat and the Slido on

00:33:54.680 --> 00:34:03.079
customization, CSS, being able to look at the gallery examples and, you know, make your

