website, your blog look the way that you'd like.

00:34:05.160 --> 00:34:10.600
But any kind of tips or feature, upcoming features on making like that kind of

00:34:10.600 --> 00:34:12.600
stylization easier?

00:34:14.760 --> 00:34:20.879
So one that I will point to for 1.3 that we did and is available in the 1.3 build right

00:34:20.879 --> 00:34:22.840
now, it's not super well documented.

00:34:22.840 --> 00:34:25.679
But I think if you find the release notes for 1.3, there's a link to some better

00:34:25.679 --> 00:34:30.840
documentation. One of the one of the one great thing about Cordo is the grid system

00:34:30.840 --> 00:34:34.959
that it has that sort of lays out the page and lets you lay out different elements and

00:34:34.959 --> 00:34:36.120
have sidebars and things.

00:34:36.120 --> 00:34:37.199
And that's a great thing about it.

00:34:37.479 --> 00:34:41.320
That's also a terrible thing about it because it's quite opinionated about the size of

00:34:41.320 --> 00:34:45.800
everything. And so that's been a challenge for people, I think, who have different

00:34:45.800 --> 00:34:49.600
opinions about the size of things, not they don't share our opinions.

00:34:50.320 --> 00:34:56.560
So starting in 1.3, we've tried to make it a lot easier for people to actually control

00:34:56.560 --> 00:35:00.719
the grid system and call the size and position, not necessarily the position, but

00:35:00.719 --> 00:35:05.280
basically to say, you know, how what do you want your widths and margins to be inside of

00:35:05.280 --> 00:35:10.280
our grid system? And that lets you make the content wider or make the sidebar smaller

00:35:10.280 --> 00:35:11.679
or make the sidebar wider.

00:35:12.479 --> 00:35:17.000
And we've got pretty simple ways for you to configure those things, be either YAML or

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:22.120
SCSS that should cascade through the grid system appropriately.

00:35:22.120 --> 00:35:26.320
So if people have a chance to give that a spin, you know, I found it makes a really big

00:35:26.320 --> 00:35:30.679
difference for things like sidebars that have long text or other scenarios where you

00:35:30.679 --> 00:35:35.800
really get sort of you get some pain from the fact that Cordo has such strong opinions

00:35:35.800 --> 00:35:37.639
about how narrow and wide things need to be.

00:35:38.159 --> 00:35:42.679
So that's a simple, simple thing for people to play with starting in 1.3.

00:35:43.239 --> 00:35:48.120
Aside from that, I think the one other thing that Carlos just did that is fun is

00:35:48.639 --> 00:35:54.280
extending our theming to Mermaid, which is really nice for using Mermaid diagrams.

00:35:54.280 --> 00:35:59.040
You won't if you're in a dark theme, you won't be confronted with a glaring, bright

00:35:59.479 --> 00:36:02.719
diagram, but instead a nice, consistent themed diagram.

00:36:03.639 --> 00:36:10.040
So one of the things that we are working on for 1.3, so the Mermaid theming was one of

00:36:10.040 --> 00:36:15.719
those things that Charles mentioned, is actually sort of documenting and figuring out

00:36:15.719 --> 00:36:20.800
what are the CSS and SCSS variables that are available in general for a theme so other

00:36:20.800 --> 00:36:22.520
packages can use them as well.

00:36:23.360 --> 00:36:26.919
So we forward SCSS variables to proper CSS variables.

00:36:26.919 --> 00:36:32.399
So if you're just producing on your own custom JavaScript or your own custom Python

00:36:32.399 --> 00:36:36.479
output things like we know we're making, we're going through the trouble of figuring out

00:36:36.479 --> 00:36:38.080
how to make those available for you.

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:40.320
So they're themed automatically and things of that sort.

00:36:41.399 --> 00:36:46.959
Rich Iannone, who's the author of GT, who is the package for sort of producing really nice

00:36:46.959 --> 00:36:49.360
tables, has been working with me on that.

00:36:49.360 --> 00:36:54.719
So we're looking forward to have the kind of like really nicely integrated support for

00:36:54.719 --> 00:36:59.439
theming that will work consistently sort of across packages so that folks that are

00:36:59.439 --> 00:37:05.040
authoring these can just actually have a consistent look depending, independent of like

00:37:05.040 --> 00:37:08.760
the theme they chose or the environment in which things are executing.

00:37:08.760 --> 00:37:13.840
So that's another place where we think we can do better than we have right now in CSS.

00:37:13.840 --> 00:37:18.360
And so that's something that we expect to have a number of improvements already in 1.3,

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:20.600
but we'll be continually working on that.

00:37:22.959 --> 00:37:26.520
And one just one thing to note about the one other note about the grid system that's

00:37:26.520 --> 00:37:30.320
important to distinguish is there's really two resources that you you could use if

00:37:30.320 --> 00:37:31.959
you're really thinking about the core of grid system.

00:37:31.959 --> 00:37:37.040
One is just reading about CSS grid, which is what Cordo uses as a grid system and is

00:37:37.040 --> 00:37:39.840
available. You can just use CSS grid from within Cordo.

00:37:40.959 --> 00:37:45.520
Then there's if you look on our website under the documentation under article layout,

00:37:45.959 --> 00:37:50.479
you'll find essentially a higher level grid system that we've built on top of CSS grid

00:37:50.879 --> 00:37:54.679
that lets you sort of dock things to different positions in the page across the width of

00:37:54.679 --> 00:37:59.120
the page. It looks a little closer like what you might see as LaTeX geometry.

00:37:59.800 --> 00:38:05.000
So it looks a little more like that and is a slightly higher level thing that is more

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:06.879
constrained, but could be easier to use.

00:38:08.040 --> 00:38:12.159
That does have the benefit of working across platforms, across output formats.

00:38:13.199 --> 00:38:17.679
And so many of those layout features are available in PDFs as well as HTML.

00:38:19.959 --> 00:38:23.959
Thank you so much. So a quick terminology question.

00:38:24.080 --> 00:38:29.080
So David asks, when you are sharing your work with normies, what do you refer to the

00:38:29.120 --> 00:38:31.840
HTML hosted Cordo content?

00:38:32.120 --> 00:38:35.879
You say, have a look at my Cordo, have a look at my dynamic docs.

00:38:36.719 --> 00:38:37.919
Yeah, welcome. Any suggestion?

00:38:40.800 --> 00:38:42.280
I'm going to defer to someone else on this.

00:38:44.639 --> 00:38:45.959
I think I just say web page.

00:38:46.520 --> 00:38:51.800
I think web pages these days are I think folks have been trained or expected that web

00:38:51.800 --> 00:38:53.560
pages do update themselves.

00:38:53.600 --> 00:38:55.360
Right. Like we're used to animations.

00:38:55.399 --> 00:38:58.719
We're used to the New York Times web pages have interactive.

00:38:59.120 --> 00:39:01.080
JavaScript in them that you can manipulate.

00:39:01.120 --> 00:39:04.840
And so I think web page kind of communicates.

00:39:05.040 --> 00:39:08.360
So if you want to say like my quarter web page, if you're looking to give us a little

00:39:08.360 --> 00:39:10.080
bit of mind share, we'd appreciate it.

00:39:10.399 --> 00:39:16.600
But like I actually just use web page or my website that I built with Quarto or

00:39:16.600 --> 00:39:18.600
something like that. But I don't.

00:39:19.080 --> 00:39:23.399
My hope is that Quarto is powerful enough to sort of stay out of your way and let you

00:39:23.399 --> 00:39:26.239
think in whichever way you want so that it looks great.

00:39:26.600 --> 00:39:29.639
But in some sense, if you want to make something that is so customizable, people

00:39:29.639 --> 00:39:30.840
wouldn't even know it's Quarto.

00:39:30.879 --> 00:39:32.000
It's just incredible.

00:39:32.439 --> 00:39:37.000
Right. I want you to build the best web pages you can, not the Quarto web pages that

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:38.879
look like Quarto.

00:39:39.040 --> 00:39:40.800
I hope our Quarto pages look good.

00:39:40.879 --> 00:39:45.439
But the goal is for you to be able to make the best technical content you can.

00:39:46.760 --> 00:39:49.320
Well, thank you, team, so, so much.

00:39:49.919 --> 00:39:53.399
Really appreciate you answering all these questions.

00:39:53.719 --> 00:39:58.959
We have I know that there are a ton more and I'm sure that we can get together, share

00:39:58.959 --> 00:40:01.520
them with you and, you know, just continue the conversation.

00:40:01.560 --> 00:40:06.280
For the last closing questions that we have is how do you release Quarto?

00:40:06.879 --> 00:40:10.600
How do folks know what's the latest and if they want to stay up to date, where do

00:40:10.600 --> 00:40:15.040
they go? I think the best place to check is just the Quarto.org website.

00:40:15.239 --> 00:40:19.679
So we do keep that we keep the Quarto.org website up to date at all times.

00:40:20.080 --> 00:40:25.040
There's always a release, which is the last is the most recent stabilized version.

00:40:25.879 --> 00:40:29.840
And then there is always a pre-release available and that is basically hot off the

00:40:29.840 --> 00:40:33.679
presses. We work very hard to make those pre-releases very stable.

00:40:34.040 --> 00:40:39.199
And so we do we do try to make those sort of user runnable at all times.

00:40:39.679 --> 00:40:42.239
But those are hot off the presses.

00:40:42.239 --> 00:40:47.840
And so from time to time, we will let something slip into those pre-releases that

00:40:47.840 --> 00:40:49.679
maybe maybe doesn't deserve to be in there.

00:40:50.399 --> 00:40:52.040
So use those with a little bit of caution.

00:40:52.040 --> 00:40:54.520
But that said, like I said, you know, we run them all the time.

00:40:55.120 --> 00:40:56.120
That's what we anticipate.

00:40:56.120 --> 00:40:58.479
You know, we really work hard to try to make those high quality.

00:40:58.479 --> 00:41:03.600
So don't be don't be terrified of them, even though they're they're they're fresh.

00:41:04.159 --> 00:41:06.080
Excellent. Well, thank you.

00:41:06.320 --> 00:41:08.360
Hope everybody has a wonderful day.

00:41:08.919 --> 00:41:10.120
We can really appreciate it.

00:41:10.560 --> 00:41:12.520
Thank you all. Thank you all for joining us.

00:41:12.520 --> 00:41:14.479
This has been great. This has been great.

00:41:15.320 --> 00:41:15.600
Thank you.

